14
00:01:55,628 --> 00:01:57,529
<i>State highway patrol.</i>

15
00:01:57,597 --> 00:01:59,731
<i>There has been an accident at
Tremble Road and the expressway.</i>

16
00:02:14,779 --> 00:02:17,715
Does it go like that all day?

17
00:02:17,782 --> 00:02:20,550
I suppose, but I don't hear it.

18
00:02:53,815 --> 00:02:55,449
You're not ready at all?

19
00:02:55,517 --> 00:02:57,351
We have time.

20
00:02:57,419 --> 00:03:01,121
The first half of a football
match is just flirting.

21
00:03:01,189 --> 00:03:02,957
Well, I'd like to get there,

22
00:03:03,025 --> 00:03:05,292
grab a nice seat,
enjoy the chitchat.

23
00:03:05,360 --> 00:03:09,062
If it's a matter of you
and I having a nice lunch,

24
00:03:09,129 --> 00:03:11,765
perhaps a ride in the boats
in the park, hmm?

25
00:03:14,201 --> 00:03:16,570
You don't even know
what's good for you.

26
00:03:16,637 --> 00:03:19,338
Spending an afternoon in
the pub with our friends.

27
00:03:19,406 --> 00:03:22,542
One: They're your friends,
and recent ones at that.

28
00:03:22,610 --> 00:03:26,679
Two: I have no fond memories
of hours spent in pubs

29
00:03:26,746 --> 00:03:28,180
watching football.
Three--

30
00:03:28,247 --> 00:03:31,316
- You love football.
- No, that's my father.

31
00:03:31,384 --> 00:03:33,719
And I hate this business

32
00:03:33,787 --> 00:03:35,921
of bringing england
over in pieces.

33
00:03:35,989 --> 00:03:37,289
It's strictly for the homesick.

34
00:03:37,356 --> 00:03:40,392
But it's filled with
immigrants like us.

35
00:03:43,228 --> 00:03:47,398
How lovely your face becomes when
you tell me you need something.

36
00:03:47,466 --> 00:03:50,735
I'd be happy if you'd just
pretend to have a good time.

37
00:03:50,803 --> 00:03:54,138
Then pretend I shall.

38
00:04:05,316 --> 00:04:09,252
♪ God save our gracious queen ♪

39
00:04:09,320 --> 00:04:12,989
♪ long live our noble queen ♪

40
00:04:13,056 --> 00:04:16,358
♪ God save our queen... ♪

41
00:04:16,426 --> 00:04:19,428
Now, I want both of you
to make a pledge

42
00:04:19,496 --> 00:04:22,297
that this is the end
of football for some time.

43
00:04:22,365 --> 00:04:25,567
We beat the bloody Jerries
for the world cup, darling.

44
00:04:25,636 --> 00:04:27,870
That is the end of football.

45
00:04:27,938 --> 00:04:29,871
I'll believe that
when I see it.

46
00:04:29,939 --> 00:04:31,405
Is Lane this way about that?

47
00:04:31,473 --> 00:04:33,207
Perhaps at one time.

48
00:04:33,275 --> 00:04:35,176
But right now
he's been in the midst

49
00:04:35,244 --> 00:04:37,512
of a messy divorce
with Great Britain.

50
00:04:37,579 --> 00:04:40,348
I dare to say
my blood's running now.

51
00:04:40,415 --> 00:04:42,483
Good day to be an Englishman.

52
00:04:42,551 --> 00:04:45,786
I don't know if I caught it.
Are you an account man at the firm?

53
00:04:45,854 --> 00:04:47,921
No, financial chief.

54
00:04:47,989 --> 00:04:49,823
You should have one
give me a call.

55
00:04:49,891 --> 00:04:51,659
Well, my name's on the door.

56
00:04:51,726 --> 00:04:54,962
I don't find britain any more
moral than here nowadays.

57
00:04:55,030 --> 00:04:57,265
The boys look like girls
and the girls,

58
00:04:57,332 --> 00:05:00,635
they don't seem to be concerned
with manners, do they?

59
00:05:00,702 --> 00:05:02,935
I find New York
better than London

60
00:05:03,003 --> 00:05:06,206
because 50 miles away, things
are infinitely more wholesome.

61
00:05:06,274 --> 00:05:09,409
You'll have your farmland.
Give it some time.

62
00:05:09,477 --> 00:05:11,811
She wants to raise hogs.

63
00:05:15,216 --> 00:05:17,150
Just take the last booth.

64
00:05:17,217 --> 00:05:18,584
Kenny?

65
00:05:20,153 --> 00:05:22,555
Oh, hi.
What are you doing here?

66
00:05:22,622 --> 00:05:24,290
Trying to get
ptomaine poisoning.

67
00:05:28,061 --> 00:05:30,563
- I'll see you at the office.
- Unless you have plans.

68
00:05:30,630 --> 00:05:32,964
Oh, no.
It's Cynthia's uncle.

69
00:05:33,032 --> 00:05:35,500
He's trying to break into radio.
I'm gonna try and talk him out of it.

70
00:05:35,568 --> 00:05:37,235
I'd love to meet him.

71
00:05:37,303 --> 00:05:39,170
He's painfully shy.

72
00:05:39,238 --> 00:05:40,471
I get it.

73
00:05:40,539 --> 00:05:42,507
You want to be alone.

74
00:05:42,575 --> 00:05:43,541
Do you mind?

75
00:05:53,451 --> 00:05:55,919
<i>Okay, now on to new business.</i>

76
00:05:55,986 --> 00:05:57,787
- Roger?
- Nope.

77
00:05:57,855 --> 00:05:59,389
- Pete?
- No.

78
00:05:59,457 --> 00:06:01,458
- Mr. Cooper?
- No, dear.

79
00:06:01,526 --> 00:06:03,427
- Don?
- Nope.

80
00:06:03,494 --> 00:06:04,961
Very well, then.

81
00:06:05,029 --> 00:06:06,696
If there are any addendums
for the minutes,

82
00:06:06,763 --> 00:06:08,264
please give them
to me by 4:00.

83
00:06:08,332 --> 00:06:10,466
Excuse me, gentlemen.
If I may.

84
00:06:10,534 --> 00:06:12,401
I have a bit of new business.

85
00:06:12,469 --> 00:06:16,071
- Taking leave again?
- Not at all.

86
00:06:17,441 --> 00:06:19,108
I don't know if you're aware,

87
00:06:19,175 --> 00:06:21,343
but England won the World Cup.

88
00:06:21,410 --> 00:06:22,910
Cup of what?

89
00:06:22,978 --> 00:06:26,748
Anyway, I've begun a bit of a
friendship with Edwin Baker,

90
00:06:26,815 --> 00:06:29,417
senior vice president
of public relations

91
00:06:29,485 --> 00:06:32,186
for Jaguar cars incorporated.

92
00:06:32,255 --> 00:06:35,323
Completely unprovoked,
he made it clear

93
00:06:35,391 --> 00:06:38,626
that since their impending
merger with BMC,

94
00:06:38,693 --> 00:06:41,362
they're looking
for a new agency

95
00:06:41,429 --> 00:06:43,497
to break them
into the American market.

96
00:06:43,565 --> 00:06:45,599
Dinner is set.

97
00:06:45,667 --> 00:06:47,768
- Yowza!
- Spectacular.

98
00:06:47,835 --> 00:06:49,703
<i>- I want one.</i>
- So, Mr. Pryce,

99
00:06:49,771 --> 00:06:52,205
- that's Jaguar, like the cat?
- Indeed.

100
00:06:52,274 --> 00:06:55,207
Why are you smiling?

101
00:06:55,276 --> 00:06:58,244
Jaguar, well, we'd probably
have to hire 10 people

102
00:06:58,312 --> 00:07:00,012
who will be on
the payroll for months.

103
00:07:00,080 --> 00:07:01,648
Are you sure we can afford it?

104
00:07:01,715 --> 00:07:04,216
My lordy.
New business.

105
00:07:04,285 --> 00:07:05,752
Not here, sir.

106
00:07:05,819 --> 00:07:08,921
I suppose if you brought in
an account of this stature,

107
00:07:08,989 --> 00:07:10,855
I might said
something different.

108
00:07:10,923 --> 00:07:13,224
It's $3 million, tops.

109
00:07:13,293 --> 00:07:15,059
It's a car and you know it.

110
00:07:15,127 --> 00:07:17,429
You know, I'd be happy
to ride shotgun.

111
00:07:17,497 --> 00:07:20,165
If nothing else, I could pick up the
check and make you look important.

112
00:07:20,232 --> 00:07:22,033
I think that would make
you look important.

113
00:07:22,101 --> 00:07:24,403
But, honestly, Lane,
if you want any of us along,

114
00:07:24,470 --> 00:07:26,304
Cooper speaks British.

115
00:07:26,371 --> 00:07:29,239
I believe Edwin and I
relate to one another

116
00:07:29,308 --> 00:07:31,776
on matters both business
and personal.

117
00:07:31,843 --> 00:07:33,778
Englishman to Englishman.

118
00:07:35,814 --> 00:07:37,114
I love that car.

119
00:07:42,353 --> 00:07:44,187
Should someone give
him a few pointers?

120
00:07:44,254 --> 00:07:46,790
- That's a good idea.
- I'm terribly busy.

121
00:07:46,857 --> 00:07:48,591
- Roger.
- I'd be glad to.

122
00:07:53,263 --> 00:07:55,732
Oh, Don.
Just a minute.

123
00:07:55,800 --> 00:07:58,967
Trudy dictated directions
to Clara for Saturday night.

124
00:07:59,035 --> 00:08:01,169
I promise, no charades,
no bridge,

125
00:08:01,237 --> 00:08:03,238
just good home cooking
and drinks.

126
00:08:03,306 --> 00:08:05,173
This Saturday
I think we're going away.

127
00:08:05,241 --> 00:08:06,675
I doubt that.

128
00:08:06,743 --> 00:08:08,410
Trudy will only act
on a certainty.

129
00:08:08,478 --> 00:08:10,011
Okay.

130
00:08:10,079 --> 00:08:11,814
Thank you.

131
00:08:13,949 --> 00:08:15,950
- Dawn, can you get Mrs. Draper?
- She's inside.

132
00:08:18,420 --> 00:08:20,521
I'm almost done.

133
00:08:20,589 --> 00:08:23,558
So, I want you to call your new
best friend Trudy Campbell

134
00:08:23,625 --> 00:08:25,593
and tell her that we're
unavailable this weekend.

135
00:08:25,661 --> 00:08:27,462
You already said
we were coming.

136
00:08:27,529 --> 00:08:28,929
To who?

137
00:08:28,997 --> 00:08:31,264
I don't know.
Trudy said you did.

138
00:08:31,332 --> 00:08:33,299
Well, she got this far
by subterfuge.

139
00:08:33,368 --> 00:08:35,469
She won't feel bad when
you pull the plug on it.

140
00:08:35,536 --> 00:08:37,170
I like her.

141
00:08:37,238 --> 00:08:39,606
I like her, too.
But Saturday night in the suburbs?

142
00:08:39,674 --> 00:08:41,475
That's when you really want
to blow your brains out.

143
00:08:41,542 --> 00:08:43,910
If you want to tell her,
you call her.

144
00:08:48,181 --> 00:08:50,516
Hey, where's Stan and Ginsberg?

145
00:08:50,584 --> 00:08:53,185
Why? Do you have something
you want to tell them?

146
00:08:53,253 --> 00:08:54,553
No.

147
00:08:58,157 --> 00:08:59,958
Listen,
about this morning--

148
00:09:00,026 --> 00:09:02,260
- I thought we had a pact.
- It's not about the pact.

149
00:09:02,327 --> 00:09:04,962
It has nothing to do with the pact.
The pact still stands.

150
00:09:05,030 --> 00:09:06,631
Then why didn't you
introduce me?

151
00:09:06,699 --> 00:09:08,266
I'm a copywriter.
I'm not gonna take your job.

152
00:09:10,969 --> 00:09:13,237
I'd love a shred of privacy.
Just a shred.

153
00:09:13,305 --> 00:09:15,206
You know?
Is that too much to ask?

154
00:09:17,442 --> 00:09:19,943
Okay, listen.

155
00:09:20,011 --> 00:09:22,145
You know I write stories.

156
00:09:22,213 --> 00:09:24,014
You're still doing that?

157
00:09:24,081 --> 00:09:26,450
Well, I decided
to fly under the radar.

158
00:09:26,518 --> 00:09:30,521
I have a nom de plume and, well,
I've had quite a bit of success

159
00:09:30,588 --> 00:09:33,290
in a particular genre
and he's from Farrar Straus.

160
00:09:33,357 --> 00:09:36,358
Wow, that's exciting.

161
00:09:36,427 --> 00:09:37,993
I guess.

162
00:09:38,061 --> 00:09:40,029
Cynthia's trying to talk
them into taking the best 20

163
00:09:40,096 --> 00:09:41,497
and turning them
into a collection.

164
00:09:41,565 --> 00:09:44,467
20?
When do you do this?

165
00:09:44,535 --> 00:09:46,969
I started turning most
of my dinners into drinks.

166
00:09:47,037 --> 00:09:50,505
And if I have only one, I'm in
pretty good shape when I get home.

167
00:09:50,573 --> 00:09:54,108
So, what is it?

168
00:09:54,176 --> 00:09:57,145
It's between fantasy
and science fiction.

169
00:09:57,212 --> 00:09:59,748
Robots and planets and things.
There's whole magazines.

170
00:09:59,816 --> 00:10:02,317
No, I mean what's
your pen name?

171
00:10:03,986 --> 00:10:05,719
Fine.
It's Ben Hargrove.

172
00:10:07,422 --> 00:10:09,189
Anyway, I could have
introduced you,

173
00:10:09,257 --> 00:10:11,525
and that was wrong,
but I just...

174
00:10:11,593 --> 00:10:13,561
I don't know.

175
00:10:13,628 --> 00:10:16,596
Well, I wish
I felt more relieved.

176
00:10:16,664 --> 00:10:19,666
It's probably not gonna happen.

177
00:10:19,733 --> 00:10:21,401
And listen,
the pact still stands.

178
00:10:21,469 --> 00:10:23,003
If I go anywhere,
you go with me.

179
00:10:23,071 --> 00:10:24,804
Okay.

180
00:10:30,478 --> 00:10:32,178
So that's some big news.

181
00:10:32,245 --> 00:10:34,513
Are you here to put in
a good word for yourself?

182
00:10:34,581 --> 00:10:37,350
No.
A little bird told med

183
00:10:37,417 --> 00:10:40,453
you got an RFP from Jaguar.
And that is a very good sign.

184
00:10:40,520 --> 00:10:42,288
Yes, I was just going over it.

185
00:10:48,827 --> 00:10:52,130
Request for proposal.
Jaguar. Blah, blah.

186
00:10:52,198 --> 00:10:55,100
"One, have you ever
been fired off an account?"

187
00:10:55,167 --> 00:10:56,901
There are worse ones than that.

188
00:11:00,006 --> 00:11:03,508
Would you take a little bit
of unsolicited advice?

189
00:11:05,010 --> 00:11:07,645
It's not pride that's
keeping me from asking.

190
00:11:07,713 --> 00:11:10,214
I certainly am aware that
you're skilled in this arena.

191
00:11:10,281 --> 00:11:11,849
I was.

192
00:11:11,917 --> 00:11:14,752
Now I guess I'm professor
emeritus of accounts.

193
00:11:14,820 --> 00:11:18,088
Look, most people will tell you
it's hard to make a mistake.

194
00:11:18,156 --> 00:11:19,789
I mean, you just lie.

195
00:11:19,857 --> 00:11:21,024
But that won't
get you anywhere.

196
00:11:22,593 --> 00:11:25,729
The beauty of this dinner
is that if you do it right,

197
00:11:25,796 --> 00:11:28,398
you can actually have him
tell you all the answers.

198
00:11:28,465 --> 00:11:31,167
In fact, I once got a guy from Dr.
Scholl's to fill it out for me.

199
00:11:31,235 --> 00:11:34,504
There'll be plenty of drinks.

200
00:11:34,572 --> 00:11:36,839
Not for you.
You order a scotch, rocks and water.

201
00:11:36,907 --> 00:11:38,941
You drink half of it
till it turns see-through.

202
00:11:39,009 --> 00:11:42,545
- You get another.
- Very good.

203
00:11:42,612 --> 00:11:45,380
And then, well, then it's
kind of like being on a date.

204
00:11:45,448 --> 00:11:47,049
Flattery, I suppose.

205
00:11:47,116 --> 00:11:49,251
Within reason.

206
00:11:49,318 --> 00:11:51,786
But I find it's best
to smile and sit there

207
00:11:51,854 --> 00:11:54,856
like you've got no place
to go and just let them talk.

208
00:11:54,924 --> 00:11:58,426
Somewhere in the middle of the entree,
they'll throw out something revealing.

209
00:11:58,493 --> 00:12:00,662
And you want to wait till
dessert to pounce on it.

210
00:12:00,729 --> 00:12:02,430
You know, let them
know you've got

211
00:12:02,497 --> 00:12:04,532
the same problem he has,
whatever it is.

212
00:12:04,600 --> 00:12:07,435
And then you're in
a conspiracy.

213
00:12:07,502 --> 00:12:10,271
The basis of
a "friendship."

214
00:12:10,338 --> 00:12:12,540
Then you whip out the form.

215
00:12:12,607 --> 00:12:14,575
What if I don't have
the same problem?

216
00:12:14,642 --> 00:12:16,510
It'll probably
just be something like

217
00:12:16,578 --> 00:12:18,512
he drinks too much, he gambles.

218
00:12:18,580 --> 00:12:20,281
I once went on
a five-minute tear

219
00:12:20,348 --> 00:12:22,349
about how my mother loved
my father more than me.

220
00:12:22,417 --> 00:12:24,017
And I can assure you
that is impossible.

221
00:12:24,085 --> 00:12:26,219
Very good, then.

222
00:12:26,287 --> 00:12:28,621
And if, for some reason,
he's more reserved?

223
00:12:28,689 --> 00:12:30,590
Just reverse it.

224
00:12:30,657 --> 00:12:32,525
Feed him your own
personal morsel.

225
00:12:32,593 --> 00:12:34,927
Oh, I see.

226
00:12:37,264 --> 00:12:38,831
That's it.

227
00:12:38,899 --> 00:12:41,266
Get your answers,
be nice to the waiter,

228
00:12:41,334 --> 00:12:42,767
and don't let him
near the check.

229
00:12:42,835 --> 00:12:45,170
Thank you very much.

230
00:12:45,238 --> 00:12:48,073
Oh, and find out everything you can
about him before you get there.

231
00:12:48,141 --> 00:12:50,041
- That I've done.
- And you still like him?

232
00:12:50,110 --> 00:12:52,611
- I do.
- Let it show.

233
00:12:57,649 --> 00:13:00,084
<i>I finally got Mrs. Campbell on the line.</i>

234
00:13:02,887 --> 00:13:05,189
Trudy, I'm glad I got
a hold of you.

235
00:13:05,257 --> 00:13:07,825
- I have some bad news.
- No, you don't.

236
00:13:07,892 --> 00:13:09,827
We're building the whole
party around you.

237
00:13:09,894 --> 00:13:12,329
You see, I'm afraid
we're not free.

238
00:13:12,396 --> 00:13:14,498
Don, do you want to go down
your list of excuses

239
00:13:14,565 --> 00:13:16,366
and I'll combat each one
individually?

240
00:13:16,434 --> 00:13:18,335
Or should we just skip
to the end?

241
00:13:18,402 --> 00:13:21,037
If you can't make it Saturday,
I will reschedule.

242
00:13:21,105 --> 00:13:22,639
It's going to happen.

243
00:13:22,706 --> 00:13:24,774
And I promise you'll have
a good time.

244
00:13:24,842 --> 00:13:27,310
It's too bad your husband
can't close a deal like this.

245
00:13:27,378 --> 00:13:29,711
We both know he's doing
just fine.

246
00:13:29,779 --> 00:13:31,280
7:30.

247
00:13:32,849 --> 00:13:34,883
Who's hungry?

248
00:13:43,126 --> 00:13:45,059
Are you okay?

249
00:13:45,127 --> 00:13:47,128
I saw you getting
a little green in there.

250
00:13:47,196 --> 00:13:49,797
Those movies are gruesome.

251
00:13:49,865 --> 00:13:52,500
I think we should go
back to riding horses.

252
00:13:52,568 --> 00:13:54,935
That must have been something.

253
00:13:55,003 --> 00:13:57,205
Why don't you
have a license yet?

254
00:13:57,273 --> 00:13:59,207
I grew up in Manhattan.

255
00:13:59,275 --> 00:14:00,907
Just wasn't necessary.

256
00:14:00,975 --> 00:14:02,609
I like going down to the city.

257
00:14:02,677 --> 00:14:04,878
There's so much to do.

258
00:14:04,945 --> 00:14:07,347
Well, maybe you'll move
there when you get older.

259
00:14:07,415 --> 00:14:10,917
Then you'll get married
and you'll move back here.

260
00:14:10,985 --> 00:14:14,020
I'm not getting married
until after college...

261
00:14:14,088 --> 00:14:16,455
If my parents still let me go.

262
00:14:16,523 --> 00:14:18,057
What?

263
00:14:18,124 --> 00:14:20,859
Didn't you hear
about the sniper

264
00:14:20,927 --> 00:14:22,761
at the University
of Texas today?

265
00:14:22,829 --> 00:14:25,698
Aren't you going to Ohio State?
It doesn't matter.

266
00:14:25,765 --> 00:14:28,767
Just two weeks after
those nurses in Chicago--

267
00:14:28,835 --> 00:14:31,504
They don't want me
out there by myself.

268
00:14:31,572 --> 00:14:34,339
Don't let them scare you.

269
00:14:34,407 --> 00:14:36,374
I don't know.

270
00:14:38,544 --> 00:14:42,414
Things seem so random
all of a sudden.

271
00:14:44,550 --> 00:14:47,785
And time feels like
it's speeding up.

272
00:14:47,853 --> 00:14:49,786
It does,

273
00:14:49,854 --> 00:14:52,055
doesn't it?

274
00:14:52,123 --> 00:14:56,159
I remember when the summer seemed
as long as the school year.

275
00:14:56,228 --> 00:14:59,597
I used to go every spring
to the botanical gardens.

276
00:14:59,664 --> 00:15:03,133
And this year, look,
it's already August.

277
00:15:03,201 --> 00:15:05,868
In the Bronx?
My family donated some of that.

278
00:15:05,936 --> 00:15:09,272
- Really?
- Well, generations ago.

279
00:15:09,340 --> 00:15:11,608
We should go some Sunday soon.

280
00:15:11,675 --> 00:15:13,743
We'd be VIPs

281
00:15:13,810 --> 00:15:16,145
Who's going to drive?

282
00:15:16,213 --> 00:15:19,249
We'll take turns.
Give each other lessons.

283
00:15:21,884 --> 00:15:25,086
<i>Okay, that's 15 minutes, everybody.</i>

284
00:15:25,154 --> 00:15:26,888
<i>Back to the salt mines.</i>

285
00:15:26,956 --> 00:15:28,990
We should go back in.

286
00:15:29,058 --> 00:15:31,226
Don't want to miss the mayhem.

287
00:15:41,203 --> 00:15:43,571
What's Ken's wife's name?

288
00:15:43,639 --> 00:15:45,974
I can't remember.

289
00:15:46,041 --> 00:15:48,576
She sent me the nicest
thank-you card for the party.

290
00:15:50,112 --> 00:15:51,946
Why don't you wear
the sport coat I got you?

291
00:15:52,014 --> 00:15:54,047
It's the country.

292
00:15:54,115 --> 00:15:55,749
You should slow down.

293
00:15:55,817 --> 00:15:57,617
I'm timing this
for when we arrive.

294
00:15:57,685 --> 00:15:59,686
I want to hit the doorbell
with my chin.

295
00:15:59,754 --> 00:16:01,755
You know, this could be fun.

296
00:16:01,823 --> 00:16:03,223
How's that work?

297
00:16:03,291 --> 00:16:04,992
You don't think there's
any chance you could

298
00:16:05,059 --> 00:16:07,161
have a conversation with
another couple as friends?

299
00:16:07,228 --> 00:16:08,895
What about your actor friends?

300
00:16:08,962 --> 00:16:10,529
I don't think
there was any business

301
00:16:10,597 --> 00:16:12,865
or financial realities
discussed the whole time.

302
00:16:12,933 --> 00:16:16,169
Don, I had to invite your
accountant to your birthday party.

303
00:16:16,236 --> 00:16:18,570
Frank's been very
important to me, okay?

304
00:16:22,709 --> 00:16:25,476
You're driving.
Now go change.

305
00:16:29,448 --> 00:16:31,883
Incredible, right?

306
00:16:31,951 --> 00:16:35,120
We keep expecting to open the doors
and see a tiny orchestra in there.

307
00:16:35,188 --> 00:16:38,356
That would be amazing.

308
00:16:38,424 --> 00:16:40,725
And it's a beautiful
piece of furniture.

309
00:16:40,793 --> 00:16:42,759
It's seven feet long.

310
00:16:42,828 --> 00:16:45,429
Wilt Chamberlain could
lie down in there.

311
00:16:45,496 --> 00:16:47,264
Why would he want to do that?

312
00:16:47,332 --> 00:16:49,733
The hostess would like you
to turn down the stereo

313
00:16:49,801 --> 00:16:51,735
for fear of waking
a nonessential guest.

314
00:16:53,738 --> 00:16:56,006
I told her she's not allowed to
talk about the baby tonight.

315
00:16:58,309 --> 00:17:00,043
Terrific.
That's him.

316
00:17:03,413 --> 00:17:05,148
- Welcome.
- I'm sorry we're late.

317
00:17:05,216 --> 00:17:07,283
You know I can't
blame the directions.

318
00:17:07,351 --> 00:17:10,186
- You have a lovely home.
- You haven't seen it.

319
00:17:10,254 --> 00:17:13,021
But it is certainly graced by
the addition of the Cosgroves.

320
00:17:13,089 --> 00:17:15,290
It's nice to see you, Don.

321
00:17:15,358 --> 00:17:17,392
Well, hello, you.

322
00:17:21,731 --> 00:17:23,332
I see a familiar red tin.

323
00:17:23,399 --> 00:17:25,433
Brownies from
William Greenberg.

324
00:17:27,070 --> 00:17:29,203
Well, hello and welcome.

325
00:17:30,405 --> 00:17:31,939
You look lovely, Trudy.

326
00:17:32,007 --> 00:17:33,741
We did it, didn't we?
We got them together.

327
00:17:33,808 --> 00:17:35,576
Tweety, look what they brought.

328
00:17:35,643 --> 00:17:36,878
Doesn't it make you homesick?

329
00:17:36,945 --> 00:17:38,946
I'm sorry there are no bakeries

330
00:17:39,014 --> 00:17:41,548
or Greenbergs in Cos Cob.

331
00:17:41,616 --> 00:17:44,352
Can we put them in the icebox?
Could everyone try it my way?

332
00:17:44,419 --> 00:17:46,887
I'm going to devil some eggs
if the girls want to help.

333
00:17:46,954 --> 00:17:48,421
Megan, you want to take
Don's drink order?

334
00:17:48,489 --> 00:17:49,822
Big and brown.

335
00:17:49,891 --> 00:17:52,092
Trudy, I love your touch.

336
00:17:52,159 --> 00:17:53,927
It's almost rustic.
Am I wrong?

337
00:17:53,995 --> 00:17:56,396
That may take longer
than you like.

338
00:17:57,831 --> 00:17:59,565
Ken just handed it to me.

339
00:18:00,901 --> 00:18:02,467
Do you like the music?

340
00:18:02,535 --> 00:18:04,603
I do.

341
00:18:04,670 --> 00:18:07,039
You know, I've never lived
on the ground floor before.

342
00:18:07,107 --> 00:18:08,673
And we don't share any walls,

343
00:18:08,741 --> 00:18:10,542
so I can make it
as loud as I want.

344
00:18:10,610 --> 00:18:13,045
But we're not gonna.
Trudy has ground rules.

345
00:18:13,113 --> 00:18:14,947
No work talk, no baby talk.

346
00:18:15,015 --> 00:18:16,415
And you get the big steak.

347
00:18:16,482 --> 00:18:18,349
Excuse me?

348
00:18:18,417 --> 00:18:20,952
Look,

349
00:18:21,020 --> 00:18:23,955
I'm not gonna pretend it's not a
big deal to us that you came out.

350
00:18:24,023 --> 00:18:26,024
Oh, come on.

351
00:18:26,091 --> 00:18:27,392
We're long overdue.

352
00:18:31,897 --> 00:18:33,997
I remember asking you
over to dinner

353
00:18:34,065 --> 00:18:36,099
when we first got married.

354
00:18:36,167 --> 00:18:38,135
That was another lifetime.

355
00:18:38,202 --> 00:18:41,004
Well, at least for me.

356
00:18:42,473 --> 00:18:45,475
Mmm, beef's brilliant,

357
00:18:45,543 --> 00:18:47,945
but it would be difficult to
do those tomatoes one better.

358
00:18:50,047 --> 00:18:52,114
Ever done any gardening?

359
00:18:52,182 --> 00:18:55,151
- No.
- Well, I'm quite keen on it now.

360
00:18:55,218 --> 00:18:58,554
Three years in north Africa,
scarcely a blade of grass,

361
00:18:58,621 --> 00:19:00,189
living like a dog.

362
00:19:00,257 --> 00:19:02,391
Yes.

363
00:19:02,459 --> 00:19:06,027
I've heard men talk with dark
permanence about those years.

364
00:19:06,095 --> 00:19:07,963
Not me.

365
00:19:08,030 --> 00:19:10,131
Best days of my life.

366
00:19:10,199 --> 00:19:12,600
Oh, well,

367
00:19:12,668 --> 00:19:15,536
then I suppose
you must miss it.

368
00:19:15,604 --> 00:19:17,439
You must have some melancholy.

369
00:19:17,506 --> 00:19:20,842
No, it's just how
I associate with my youth.

370
00:19:23,078 --> 00:19:25,045
What about your war?

371
00:19:25,113 --> 00:19:28,449
I volunteered for combat
on numerous occasions,

372
00:19:28,516 --> 00:19:31,918
but spent most of the war as a
supply assistant in Rosyth.

373
00:19:31,987 --> 00:19:34,154
Well, everyone
played their part.

374
00:19:34,222 --> 00:19:36,457
That was britain at its best.

375
00:19:36,524 --> 00:19:38,157
Yes.

376
00:19:41,295 --> 00:19:44,364
So I'm glad to hear that
America has been good for you.

377
00:19:44,431 --> 00:19:47,266
And your wife
is pleased, I assume?

378
00:19:47,334 --> 00:19:49,768
I'll be honest with you, Lane.

379
00:19:51,671 --> 00:19:53,872
I haven't a complaint
in the world.

380
00:19:53,939 --> 00:19:56,674
Well, that's too bad, isn't it?

381
00:20:04,426 --> 00:20:06,359
So the Coe family claims it was them.
Coes' Cob.

382
00:20:06,428 --> 00:20:09,463
Which became through
yankee arrogance Cos Cob.

383
00:20:09,531 --> 00:20:12,733
Of course, it also sounds a lot like
the Algonquin word for briefcase.

384
00:20:14,402 --> 00:20:16,804
Ken, where have you and--

385
00:20:16,871 --> 00:20:19,204
Where have you two
made your home?

386
00:20:19,272 --> 00:20:21,206
We're in Jackson
Heights, Queens.

387
00:20:21,274 --> 00:20:23,743
It's very down to earth.
A lot of workers.

388
00:20:23,811 --> 00:20:25,912
I keep telling them
to move out to the country.

389
00:20:25,979 --> 00:20:27,847
Well, we both work in the city

390
00:20:27,915 --> 00:20:29,849
and my parents
aren't like Trudy's.

391
00:20:29,917 --> 00:20:31,851
Help from them comes with a
lot of strings attached.

392
00:20:31,919 --> 00:20:34,018
It is beautiful out here.

393
00:20:34,086 --> 00:20:37,055
The air is so fresh and all
the trees and the grass.

394
00:20:37,122 --> 00:20:38,790
I grew up in rural Vermont.

395
00:20:38,858 --> 00:20:41,860
Kids throwing their bikes on the
front lawn is not the country to me.

396
00:20:41,928 --> 00:20:44,329
You miss the horse shit, huh?

397
00:20:46,432 --> 00:20:47,933
Don!

398
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:50,501
I grew up in the country,
too, and I don't miss walking

399
00:20:50,569 --> 00:20:52,169
to an outhouse in
the middle of winter.

400
00:20:52,236 --> 00:20:55,372
Well, it's more
civilized than that.

401
00:20:55,440 --> 00:20:57,407
But there are a lot
of varmints.

402
00:20:58,677 --> 00:21:00,310
You should bring
that rifle home.

403
00:21:00,378 --> 00:21:03,948
You still have that?
There will be no gun in this house.

404
00:21:04,015 --> 00:21:07,283
I never liked them.
And now with that Charles Whitmore.

405
00:21:07,351 --> 00:21:09,318
Whitman.

406
00:21:09,386 --> 00:21:11,120
They say he had a brain tumor.

407
00:21:11,188 --> 00:21:12,722
He kept warning everyone.

408
00:21:12,790 --> 00:21:14,858
Without a gun would he
be able to kill his wife

409
00:21:14,925 --> 00:21:16,626
and mom and 20 other people?

410
00:21:16,694 --> 00:21:18,495
I'm sorry.

411
00:21:18,562 --> 00:21:20,396
It's the hostess' prerogative
to change the subject.

412
00:21:20,464 --> 00:21:22,531
Trudy, it bears discussion.

413
00:21:22,599 --> 00:21:25,033
One rifle for shooting
gophers is not the same

414
00:21:25,101 --> 00:21:28,103
as a frustrated ex-marine
shooting at pregnant ladies.

415
00:21:28,170 --> 00:21:29,671
You know, Kenny predicted it.

416
00:21:29,739 --> 00:21:31,473
He wrote a story that
was exactly like that.

417
00:21:31,541 --> 00:21:33,609
- Don't, Cynthia.
- Cynthia!

418
00:21:33,676 --> 00:21:34,710
What?

419
00:21:35,979 --> 00:21:39,079
Nothing, I just...

420
00:21:39,147 --> 00:21:42,917
- Honey, they don't want to talk about that.
- Why not?

421
00:21:42,985 --> 00:21:45,319
You know, if he wasn't a writer,
we never would have met.

422
00:21:45,387 --> 00:21:48,623
- I didn't know that.
- I work in publishing.

423
00:21:48,690 --> 00:21:52,259
My boss was rejecting him and I
thought it was all he could handle.

424
00:21:56,898 --> 00:21:58,732
What was the story?

425
00:21:58,799 --> 00:22:01,935
- Forget it.
- No, we want to know.

426
00:22:03,905 --> 00:22:06,372
It's called
"The Punishment Of X4."

427
00:22:06,440 --> 00:22:09,742
There's this bridge
between these two planets

428
00:22:09,809 --> 00:22:12,411
and thousands of humans
travel on it every day.

429
00:22:12,478 --> 00:22:16,048
And so there's this robot;
he does maintenance on the bridge.

430
00:22:16,115 --> 00:22:20,019
And one day, he removes a bolt

431
00:22:20,086 --> 00:22:22,755
and the bridge collapses
and everyone dies.

432
00:22:28,093 --> 00:22:30,762
There's more to it
than that, you know.

433
00:22:30,829 --> 00:22:33,397
But it's just a story.

434
00:22:33,465 --> 00:22:35,232
Why does he do it?

435
00:22:35,300 --> 00:22:37,268
Because he's a robot.

436
00:22:37,335 --> 00:22:39,003
Those people
tell him what to do

437
00:22:39,071 --> 00:22:41,005
and he doesn't have the
power to make any decisions

438
00:22:41,106 --> 00:22:43,507
except he can decide whether
that bolt's on or off.

439
00:22:45,110 --> 00:22:47,244
Or he just hates commuters.

440
00:22:49,814 --> 00:22:51,549
How long have you been writing?

441
00:22:51,583 --> 00:22:53,551
I started screwing around
in high school.

442
00:22:53,618 --> 00:22:56,753
And by the time I got a job,
I thought it would go away.

443
00:22:56,854 --> 00:22:59,021
And it mostly has.

444
00:22:59,090 --> 00:23:01,424
No one grows awaiting
to be an advertising.

445
00:23:01,459 --> 00:23:04,694
Oh, that's not true.
It's such an interesting profession to me..

446
00:23:04,761 --> 00:23:06,429
What are you to it, Megan?

447
00:23:06,497 --> 00:23:08,631
Megan came to
New York as an actress.

448
00:23:08,699 --> 00:23:12,034
If trying to be an actress
is being an actress.

449
00:23:12,103 --> 00:23:14,970
That's fascinating.
I could see it.

450
00:23:15,037 --> 00:23:18,273
But I had been in a few
agencies on auditions

451
00:23:18,374 --> 00:23:21,310
and it looked like a fun
place to get the bills paid.

452
00:23:21,377 --> 00:23:24,045
And I saw what Don
and Peggy did

453
00:23:24,114 --> 00:23:26,115
and I saw a future
for myself in it.

454
00:23:26,182 --> 00:23:27,483
That's the truth.

455
00:23:29,519 --> 00:23:32,220
Can I interest anyone
in dessert and coffee?

456
00:23:32,287 --> 00:23:34,255
- Hot or iced?
- Yes to dessert.

457
00:23:34,289 --> 00:23:36,491
Still having too much
fun for coffee.

458
00:23:43,798 --> 00:23:46,601
People talk about how there's
so much crime in the city.

459
00:23:46,701 --> 00:23:49,069
I was ripped off by the kid
who mows my lawn.

460
00:23:49,137 --> 00:23:51,805
Yes, they used to take my beer
out of the fridge in the garage.

461
00:23:51,873 --> 00:23:54,642
A fridge in the garage?
That's a good idea.

462
00:24:00,548 --> 00:24:03,116
Damn it.
I'll get the toolbox.

463
00:24:03,183 --> 00:24:05,718
I turned it on and it
just blew in my face.

464
00:24:07,387 --> 00:24:08,888
Hold this.

465
00:24:10,891 --> 00:24:12,659
Don, what are you doing?

466
00:24:14,561 --> 00:24:15,762
Look, it's Superman.

467
00:24:22,434 --> 00:24:25,336
Oh, good lord.

468
00:24:53,363 --> 00:24:54,831
What was wrong?

469
00:24:54,899 --> 00:24:57,600
The supply was turned all the way up.
It forces the valve.

470
00:24:57,668 --> 00:25:00,403
- But it stopped the leak.
- That was a coincidence.

471
00:25:00,470 --> 00:25:03,173
Grab Don's shirt.
I'll throw it in the dryer.

472
00:25:03,240 --> 00:25:05,742
Aren't we supposed to say
something about that baby?

473
00:25:05,810 --> 00:25:08,210
- Look at her.
- What an angel.

474
00:25:14,217 --> 00:25:17,352
I take no credit
for her at all.

475
00:25:17,420 --> 00:25:19,354
<i>Aw!</i>

476
00:25:21,657 --> 00:25:23,357
I'm gonna close my eyes.

477
00:25:23,425 --> 00:25:25,927
And when I open them
I want to see skyscrapers.

478
00:25:25,994 --> 00:25:28,096
Admit it, you had a great time.

479
00:25:30,766 --> 00:25:33,567
I'm too drunk for you to drive.

480
00:25:33,635 --> 00:25:35,870
We should pull over
and both sober up.

481
00:25:38,607 --> 00:25:40,874
Let's make a baby.

482
00:25:40,942 --> 00:25:43,210
No, that's impossible.

483
00:25:43,277 --> 00:25:44,845
What, isn't that
how this works?

484
00:25:46,214 --> 00:25:47,680
A baby gets you going?

485
00:25:50,218 --> 00:25:52,786
Just pull over.
This brassiere is like Fort Knox.

486
00:26:00,794 --> 00:26:02,862
The only reason
you're getting anywhere

487
00:26:02,929 --> 00:26:04,830
is because Pete scared
the shit out of me

488
00:26:04,898 --> 00:26:07,466
with his car
accident statistics

489
00:26:07,533 --> 00:26:11,770
and because I can't believe

490
00:26:11,804 --> 00:26:14,639
how much I loved watching
you fix that sink.

491
00:26:21,881 --> 00:26:23,815
Because there
was a plane crash.

492
00:26:23,883 --> 00:26:25,516
And it doesn't matter that
it's not one of Mohawk's.

493
00:26:25,584 --> 00:26:26,950
We should stop
running ads for a week

494
00:26:27,018 --> 00:26:28,418
and then just hope
that no one notices

495
00:26:28,486 --> 00:26:30,320
that Mohawk has 10 planes
that are the same model.

496
00:26:30,388 --> 00:26:32,923
Why? There's a plane crash
every day in Vietnam.

497
00:26:32,991 --> 00:26:35,224
There were seven yesterday.
It's Braniff, for Christ's sake.

498
00:26:35,293 --> 00:26:36,859
Let them eat their
award-winning work.

